At age six, in a clearing in the woods, I experienced a hallucination. The form that I saw appeared to have a kind of fractal-like, angular architecture. At the same time, it somehow seemed to imply movement, like a photograph of water reflections or the rhythmic design of a classical Greek sculpture. 

At six, I described it best by simply calling it a “fountain”.

I made my first drawings as efforts to describe the fountain I saw. It shows up over and over in my art practice.

My works are concerned with time, materiality and transformation. I produce textures and patterns that reflect the countless layers and dimensions that make up the universe.
